lts, some worn or faded, join show quilts, needlework masterpieces, and “best” quilts saved for special occasions. Texas quilts, including those made in or brought to Texas during the nineteenth century, constitute a significant number of the selections. Color photographs of related documents and material culture objects from the Briscoe Center’s collections—quilting templates, a painted bride’s box, sheet music, a homespun dress, a brass sewing bird, and political ephemera, among them—enrich the stories of many of the quilts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aQuiltszTexasvCatalogs. 0aQuiltszTexasxHistoryvCatalogs. 0aQuiltszTexasxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Katherine Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarleton, Don, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Bryant Puentes, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatterson Bresenhan, Karoline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311074532040uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/30918640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477309193423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477309193/original  a978-3-11-074532-0  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles